nodes.label: GO:0034367
nodes.Name: protein-containing complex remodeling
nodes.Definition: The acquisition, loss, or modification of macromolecules within a complex, resulting in the alteration of an existing complex.

nodes.label: GO:0004244
nodes.Name: obsolete mitochondrial inner membrane peptidase activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the maturation of mitochondrial precursor proteins delivered to the intermembrane space.

nodes.label: GO:0050065
nodes.Name: lysine-pyruvate 6-transaminase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: L-lysine + pyruvate = L-alanine + L-allysine.

nodes.label: GO:0004297
nodes.Name: obsolete plasminogen activator activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the specific cleavage of an Arg-Val bond in plasminogen to form plasmin.

nodes.label: GO:0008243
nodes.Name: obsolete plasminogen activator activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the specific cleavage of an Arg-Val bond in plasminogen to form plasmin.

nodes.label: GO:0005679
nodes.Name: obsolete chromatin remodeling complex
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Any complex that mediates dynamic changes in eukaryotic chromatin.

nodes.label: GO:0016585
nodes.Name: obsolete chromatin remodeling complex
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Any complex that mediates dynamic changes in eukaryotic chromatin.

nodes.label: GO:0047863
nodes.Name: dimethylallylcistransferase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: dimethylallyl diphosphate + isopentenyl diphosphate = diphosphate + neryl diphosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0050141
nodes.Name: obsolete nitroethane oxidase activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: nitroethane + H2O + O2 = acetaldehyde + nitrite + H2O2.

nodes.label: GO:0052664
nodes.Name: nitroalkane oxidase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: a primary nitroalkane + H2O + O2 = an aldehyde + H+ + H2O2 + nitrite; also converts secondary nitroalkanes to a ketone.

nodes.label: GO:0097084
nodes.Name: vascular associated smooth muscle cell development
nodes.Definition: The process aimed at the progression of a vascular smooth muscle cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell. A vascular smooth muscle cell is a non-striated, elongated, spindle-shaped cell found lining the blood vessels.

nodes.label: GO:0034594
nodes.Name: phosphatidylinositol trisphosphate phosphatase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: phosphatidylinositol trisphosphate + H2O = phosphatidylinositol bisphosphate + phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0052867
nodes.Name: phosphatidylinositol-1,4,5-trisphosphate 5-phosphatase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate + H2O = 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 1,4-bisphosphate + phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0010832
nodes.Name: negative regulation of myotube differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of myotube differentiation. Myotube differentiation is the process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a myotube cell. Myotubes are multinucleated cells that are formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.

nodes.label: GO:0060932
nodes.Name: His-Purkinje system cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized structural and/or functional features of a cell of the His-Purkinje system. These cells form the fibers regulate cardiac muscle contraction in the ventricles.

nodes.label: GO:0060934
nodes.Name: His-Purkinje system cell fate commitment
nodes.Definition: The commitment of cells to His-Purkinje cell fates and their capacity to differentiate into His-Purkinje cells. These cells form the fibers that regulate cardiac muscle contraction in the ventricles.

nodes.label: GO:0003283
nodes.Name: atrial septum development
nodes.Definition: The progression of the atrial septum over time, from its initial formation to the mature structure.

nodes.label: GO:0003285
nodes.Name: septum secundum development
nodes.Definition: The progression of the septum secundum over time, from its initial formation to the mature structure.

nodes.label: GO:0070269
nodes.Name: pyroptotic inflammatory response
nodes.Definition: A gasdermin-dependent inflammatory response that is associated with the generation of pyrogenic mediators such as IL-1beta and IL-18. Gasdermins are activated by caspase-1 or caspase-4/11, or by certain granzymes. In some, but not all cells, it can lead to pyroptotic programmed cell death.

nodes.label: GO:0044230
nodes.Name: host cell envelope
nodes.Definition: An envelope that surrounds a bacterial host cell and includes the host cytoplasmic membrane and everything external, encompassing the host periplasmic space, host cell wall, and host outer membrane if present.

nodes.label: GO:2000494
nodes.Name: positive regulation of interleukin-18-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of interleukin-18-mediated signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:0030946
nodes.Name: protein tyrosine phosphatase activity, metal-dependent
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: protein tyrosine phosphate + H2O = protein tyrosine + phosphate. This reaction requires metal ions.

nodes.label: GO:0004050
nodes.Name: apyrase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: a ribonucleoside 5'-triphosphate + 2 H2O = a ribonucleoside 5'-phosphate + 2 phosphate. This reaction consists of two distinct successive phosphate-releasing steps, with NDPs as intermediates. Apyrases are active against both di- and triphosphate nucleotides (NDPs and NTPs) and hydrolyze NTPs to nucleotide monophosphates (NMPs).

nodes.label: GO:0043575
nodes.Name: detection of osmotic stimulus
nodes.Definition: The series of events in which a stimulus indicating an increase or decrease in the concentration of solutes outside the organism or cell is received and converted into a molecular signal.

nodes.label: GO:0048775
nodes.Name: regulation of leucophore differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of leucophore differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:0048777
nodes.Name: positive regulation of leucophore differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of leucophore differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:2000822
nodes.Name: regulation of behavioral fear response
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of behavioral fear response.

nodes.label: GO:0047537
nodes.Name: 2-aminohexanoate transaminase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: L-2-aminohexanoate + 2-oxoglutarate = 2-oxohexanoate + L-glutamate.

nodes.label: GO:0004351
nodes.Name: glutamate decarboxylase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: L-glutamate = 4-aminobutanoate + CO2.

nodes.label: GO:0040013
nodes.Name: negative regulation of locomotion
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of locomotion of a cell or organism.

nodes.label: GO:0075200
nodes.Name: obsolete negative regulation of symbiont haustorium neck formation for entry into host
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of symbiont haustorium neck formation for entry into host. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:2000516
nodes.Name: positive regulation of CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell activation
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell activation.

nodes.label: GO:0052737
nodes.Name: pyruvate dehydrogenase (quinone) activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: a ubiquinone + H2O + pyruvate = a ubiquinol + acetate + CO2.

nodes.label: GO:0052738
nodes.Name: oxidoreductase activity, acting on the aldehyde or oxo group of donors, with a quinone or similar compound as acceptor
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which an aldehyde or ketone (oxo) group acts as a hydrogen or electron donor and reduces a quinone or similar compound.

nodes.label: GO:0045509
nodes.Name: interleukin-27 receptor activity
nodes.Definition: Combining with interleukin-27 and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.

nodes.label: GO:0045513
nodes.Name: interleukin-27 binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to interleukin-27.

nodes.label: GO:0097311
nodes.Name: bacterial biofilm matrix
nodes.Definition: A structure lying external to bacterial cells. A biofilm is an aggregate of surface-associated bacteria, and the biofilm matrix is the envelope of polymeric substances that surrounds the bacteria.

nodes.label: GO:1904745
nodes.Name: Atg1/ULK1 kinase complex assembly
nodes.Definition: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form an Atg1/UKL1 kinase complex.

nodes.label: GO:0033077
nodes.Name: T cell differentiation in thymus
nodes.Definition: The process in which a precursor cell type acquires the specialized features of a T cell via a differentiation pathway dependent upon transit through the thymus.

nodes.label: GO:1904155
nodes.Name: DN2 thymocyte differentiation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of a DN2 thymocyte. A DN2 thymocyte is a CD4-,CD8- thymocyte that is also CD44+,CD25-.

nodes.label: GO:0030368
nodes.Name: interleukin-17 receptor activity
nodes.Definition: Combining with any member of the interleukin-17 family of cytokines and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.

nodes.label: GO:1901028
nodes.Name: regulation of mitochondrial outer membrane permeabilization involved in apoptotic signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mitochondrial outer membrane permeabilization involved in apoptotic signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:0031645
nodes.Name: negative regulation of nervous system process
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a neurophysiological process.

nodes.label: GO:0050877
nodes.Name: nervous system process
nodes.Definition: A organ system process carried out by any of the organs or tissues of neurological system.

nodes.label: GO:0055013
nodes.Name: cardiac muscle cell development
nodes.Definition: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a cardiac muscle cell over time, from its formation to the mature state.

nodes.label: GO:0048068
nodes.Name: adult chitin-containing cuticle pigmentation
nodes.Definition: Establishment of the adult pattern of pigmentation in the chitin-containing cuticle of an organism. An example of this is the adult cuticle pigmentation process in Drosophila melanogaster.

nodes.label: GO:0047241
nodes.Name: lipopolysaccharide N-acetylmannosaminouronosyltransferase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: lipopolysaccharide + UDP-N-acetylmannosaminouronate = N-acetyl-beta-D-mannosaminouronosyl-1,4-lipopolysaccharide + UDP.

nodes.label: GO:1901300
nodes.Name: positive regulation of hydrogen peroxide-mediated programmed cell death
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of hydrogen peroxide-mediated programmed cell death.

nodes.label: GO:0075267
nodes.Name: aecium development
nodes.Definition: The process in which a cup-like structure containing chains of aeciospores is formed. This is characteristic of the rust fungus and typically, the first dikaryotic spores (aeciospores) are produced in the aecium.

nodes.label: GO:0075269
nodes.Name: positive regulation of aecium development
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of aecium development, a process in which a cuplike structure containing chains of aeciospores is formed.

nodes.label: GO:0019980
nodes.Name: interleukin-5 binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to interleukin-5.

nodes.label: GO:0050110
nodes.Name: obsolete endo-alpha-N-acetylgalactosaminidase activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reactions : D-galactosyl-3-(N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl)-L-serine + H2O = D-galactosyl-3-N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine + L-serine and D-galactosyl-3-(N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl)-L-threonyl + H2O = D-galactosyl-3-N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine + L-threonyl.

nodes.label: GO:0047255
nodes.Name: galactogen 6-beta-galactosyltransferase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: galactogen + UDP-galactose = 1,6-beta-D-galctosylgalactogen + UDP.

nodes.label: GO:0004653
nodes.Name: polypeptide N-acetylgalactosaminyltransferase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: UDP-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine + polypeptide = UDP + N-acetyl-D-galactosaminyl-polypeptide. This reaction is the modification of serine or threonine residues in polypeptide chains by the transfer of a N-acetylgalactose from UDP-N-acetylgalactose to the hydroxyl group of the amino acid; it is the first step in O-glycan biosynthesis.

nodes.label: GO:0060338
nodes.Name: regulation of type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of a type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:0060340
nodes.Name: positive regulation of type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of a type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:0033724
nodes.Name: erythrose-4-phosphate dehydrogenase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: D-erythrose 4-phosphate + H2O + NAD+ = 4-phospho-D-erythronate + 2 H+ + NADH.

nodes.label: GO:0048001
nodes.Name: erythrose-4-phosphate dehydrogenase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: D-erythrose 4-phosphate + H2O + NAD+ = 4-phospho-D-erythronate + 2 H+ + NADH.

nodes.label: GO:0060102
nodes.Name: collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix
nodes.Definition: A collagen and cuticulin-based noncellular, multilayered structure that is synthesized by an underlying ectodermal (hypodermal) cell layer. The cuticle serves essential functions in body morphology, locomotion, and environmental protection. An example of this component is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.

nodes.label: GO:0060106
nodes.Name: cortical layer of collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix
nodes.Definition: The cuticle layer that lies directly beneath the lipid-containing epicuticle. The cortical layer contains collagens and insoluble, non-collagenous cuticulins and is characterized by a distinct annular pattern consisting of regularly spaced annular ridges delineated by annular furrows. An example of this component is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.

nodes.label: GO:0052821
nodes.Name: DNA-7-methyladenine glycosylase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: DNA containing 7-methyladenine + H2O = DNA with abasic site + 7-methyladenine. This reaction is the hydrolysis of DNA by cleavage of the N-C1' glycosidic bond between the damaged DNA 7-methyladenine and the deoxyribose sugar to remove the 7-methyladenine, leaving an abasic site.

nodes.label: GO:1905041
nodes.Name: regulation of epithelium regeneration
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of epithelium regeneration.

nodes.label: GO:1990399
nodes.Name: epithelium regeneration
nodes.Definition: The regrowth of lost or destroyed epithelium.

nodes.label: GO:0006337
nodes.Name: nucleosome disassembly
nodes.Definition: The controlled breakdown of nucleosomes, the beadlike structural units of eukaryotic chromatin composed of histones and DNA.

nodes.label: GO:0060761
nodes.Name: negative regulation of response to cytokine stimulus
nodes.Definition: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency, or extent of a response to cytokine stimulus.

nodes.label: GO:1903970
nodes.Name: negative regulation of response to macrophage colony-stimulating factor
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of response to macrophage colony-stimulating factor.

nodes.label: GO:0016623
nodes.Name: oxidoreductase activity, acting on the aldehyde or oxo group of donors, oxygen as acceptor
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which an aldehyde or ketone (oxo) group acts as a hydrogen or electron donor and reduces oxygen.

nodes.label: GO:0046569
nodes.Name: glyoxal oxidase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: glyoxal + O2 + H2O = glyoxalate + H2O2.

nodes.label: GO:0033873
nodes.Name: petromyzonol sulfotransferase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: 3'-phospho-5'-adenylyl sulfate + 5alpha-cholane-3alpha,7alpha,12alpha,24-tetrol = 3alpha,7alpha,12alpha-trihydroxy-5alpha-cholan-24-yl sulfate + adenosine 3',5'-diphosphate + H+.

nodes.label: GO:2000857
nodes.Name: positive regulation of mineralocorticoid secretion
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of mineralocorticoid secretion.

nodes.label: GO:0044202
nodes.Name: host cell nuclear outer membrane
nodes.Definition: The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the host nuclear envelope; continuous with the endoplasmic reticulum of the host cell and sometimes studded with ribosomes.

nodes.label: GO:1904270
nodes.Name: pyroptosome complex assembly
nodes.Definition: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a pyroptosome complex.

nodes.label: GO:0034038
nodes.Name: deoxyhypusine synthase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: [eIF5A-precursor]-lysine + spermidine = [eIF5A-precursor]-deoxyhypusine + propane-1,3-diamine. Four sub-reactions have been identified,in which the intermediates remain tightly associated with the enzyme: spermidine + NAD+ = dehydrospermidine + NADH; dehydrospermidine + [enzyme]-lysine = N-(4-aminobutylidene)-[enzyme]-lysine + propane-1,3-diamine; N-(4-aminobutylidene)-[enzyme]-lysine + [eIF5A-precursor]-lysine = N-(4-aminobutylidene)-[eIF5A-precursor]-lysine + [enzyme]-lysine; N-(4-aminobutylidene)-[eIF5A-precursor]-lysine + NADH + H+ = [eIF5A-precursor]-deoxyhypusine + NAD+.

nodes.label: GO:0070662
nodes.Name: mast cell proliferation
nodes.Definition: The expansion of a mast cell population by cell division.

nodes.label: GO:0044142
nodes.Name: obsolete positive regulation of growth of symbiont on or near host surface
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the symbiont's increase in size or mass on or near the cells or tissues of the host organism.

nodes.label: GO:0075337
nodes.Name: obsolete positive regulation of growth or development of symbiont on or near host surface
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the symbiont's increase in size or mass, or its progression from an initial condition to a later condition, on or near the cells or tissues of the host organism.

nodes.label: GO:0007600
nodes.Name: sensory perception
nodes.Definition: The series of events required for an organism to receive a sensory stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. This is a neurological process.

nodes.label: GO:0051931
nodes.Name: regulation of sensory perception
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of sensory perception, the series of events required for an organism to receive a sensory stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal.

nodes.label: GO:0016121
nodes.Name: carotene catabolic process
nodes.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of carotenes, hydrocarbon carotenoids.

nodes.label: GO:0046247
nodes.Name: terpene catabolic process
nodes.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of terpenes, any of a large group of hydrocarbons made up of isoprene units.

nodes.label: GO:1902228
nodes.Name: positive regulation of macrophage colony-stimulating factor signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of macrophage colony-stimulating factor signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:1903974
nodes.Name: positive regulation of cellular response to macrophage colony-stimulating factor stimulus
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cellular response to macrophage colony-stimulating factor stimulus.

nodes.label: GO:0018814
nodes.Name: phenylacetaldoxime dehydratase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: (trans)-phenylacetaldoxime = H2O + phenylacetonitrile.

nodes.label: GO:0009519
nodes.Name: middle lamella
nodes.Definition: Layer of intercellular material, chiefly pectic substances, cementing together the primary walls of contiguous cells.

nodes.label: GO:0007519
nodes.Name: skeletal muscle tissue development
nodes.Definition: The developmental sequence of events leading to the formation of adult skeletal muscle tissue. The main events are: the fusion of myoblasts to form myotubes that increase in size by further fusion to them of myoblasts, the formation of myofibrils within their cytoplasm and the establishment of functional neuromuscular junctions with motor neurons. At this stage they can be regarded as mature muscle fibers.

nodes.label: GO:0014707
nodes.Name: branchiomeric skeletal muscle development
nodes.Definition: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the branchiomeric skeletal muscle over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The branchiomeric muscle is derived from cranial mesoderm and controls facial expression, pharyngeal and laryngeal function, operating the jaw. The muscle begins its development with the differentiation of the muscle cells and ends with the mature muscle. Branchiomeric muscles of mammals correspond to the gill musculature of fish.

nodes.label: GO:0002927
nodes.Name: archaeosine-tRNA biosynthetic process
nodes.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involved in the biosynthesis of archaeosine, an archaea-specific modified base found at position 15 in the D-loop of certain archaeal tRNAs.

nodes.label: GO:0002948
nodes.Name: archaeosine synthase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: L-glutamine + 7-cyano-7-carbaguanine15 in tRNA + H2O = L-glutamate + archaeine15 in tRNA.

nodes.label: GO:0008734
nodes.Name: L-aspartate oxidase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: L-aspartate + O2 = iminosuccinate + H2O2. Can also use fumatate as electron acceptor under anaerobic conditions, yielding succinate.

nodes.label: GO:0034349
nodes.Name: glial cell apoptotic process
nodes.Definition: Any apoptotic process in a glial cell, a non-neuronal cell of the nervous system.

nodes.label: GO:0034350
nodes.Name: regulation of glial cell apoptotic process
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of glial cell apoptotic process.

nodes.label: GO:0071831
nodes.Name: intermediate-density lipoprotein particle clearance
nodes.Definition: The process in which a intermediate-density lipoprotein particle is removed from the blood via receptor-mediated endocytosis and its constituent parts degraded.

nodes.label: GO:0042060
nodes.Name: wound healing
nodes.Definition: The series of events that restore integrity to a damaged tissue, following an injury.

nodes.label: GO:0060054
nodes.Name: positive regulation of epithelial cell proliferation involved in wound healing
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of epithelial cell proliferation, contributing to the restoration of integrity to a damaged tissue following an injury.

nodes.label: GO:0042693
nodes.Name: muscle cell fate commitment
nodes.Definition: The process in which the cellular identity of muscle cells is acquired and determined.

nodes.label: GO:1903101
nodes.Name: 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 3,5-bisphosphate catabolic process
nodes.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 3,5-bisphosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0000282
nodes.Name: cellular bud site selection
nodes.Definition: The specification of the site where a daughter cell will form, in organisms that reproduce by budding. An example of this process is found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.

nodes.label: GO:0007120
nodes.Name: axial cellular bud site selection
nodes.Definition: The process of defining the next site of bud emergence adjacent to the last site of bud emergence on a budding cell.

nodes.label: GO:0050962
nodes.Name: detection of light stimulus involved in sensory perception
nodes.Definition: The series of events in which a light stimulus is received by a cell and converted into a molecular signal as part of the sensory perception of light.

nodes.label: GO:0045171
nodes.Name: intercellular bridge
nodes.Definition: A direct connection between the cytoplasm of two cells that is formed following the completion of cleavage furrow ingression during cell division. They are usually present only briefly prior to completion of cytokinesis. However, in some cases, such as the bridges between germ cells during their development, they become stabilised.

nodes.label: GO:0045172
nodes.Name: germline ring canal
nodes.Definition: Germline specific intercellular bridge. During cyst formation in insects, ring canals interconnect the cells of the cyst, facilitating the passage of cytoplasmic components between cells.

nodes.label: GO:1902176
nodes.Name: negative regulation of oxidative stress-induced intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of an oxidative stress-induced intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:1903377
nodes.Name: negative regulation of oxidative stress-induced neuron intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of oxidative stress-induced neuron intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:2000176
nodes.Name: positive regulation of pro-T cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of pro-T cell differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:0001661
nodes.Name: conditioned taste aversion
nodes.Definition: A conditioned aversion to a specific chemical compound as a result of that compound being coupled with a noxious stimulus.

nodes.label: GO:0007631
nodes.Name: feeding behavior
nodes.Definition: Behavior associated with the intake of food.

nodes.label: GO:0072590
nodes.Name: N-acetyl-L-aspartate-L-glutamate ligase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + N-acetyl-L-aspartate + L-glutamate = ADP + phosphate + N-acetylaspartyl-glutamate.

nodes.label: GO:0010487
nodes.Name: thermospermine synthase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: S-adenosyl-L-methioninamine + spermidine = S-methyl-5'-thioadenosine + thermospermine + H+.

nodes.label: GO:0090303
nodes.Name: positive regulation of wound healing
nodes.Definition: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of the series of events that restore integrity to a damaged tissue, following an injury.

nodes.label: GO:0042015
nodes.Name: interleukin-20 binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to interleukin-20.

nodes.label: GO:0042016
nodes.Name: interleukin-20 receptor activity
nodes.Definition: Combining with interleukin-20 and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.

nodes.label: GO:0044204
nodes.Name: host cell nuclear matrix
nodes.Definition: The dense fibrillar network lying on the inner side of the host nuclear membrane.

nodes.label: GO:0052745
nodes.Name: inositol phosphate phosphatase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: inositol phosphate(n) + H2O = inositol phosphate(n-1) + phosphate. This reaction is the removal of a phosphate group from an inositol phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0075247
nodes.Name: aeciospore formation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a dikaryotic spore of typically a rust fungus is produced in an aecium; in heteroecious rusts, the aeciospore is a spore stage that infects the alternate host.

nodes.label: GO:0075248
nodes.Name: regulation of aeciospore formation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of aeciospore formation, a process in which a dikaryotic spore of typically a rust fungus is produced in an aecium.

nodes.label: GO:0050817
nodes.Name: coagulation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a fluid solution, or part of it, changes into a solid or semisolid mass.

nodes.label: GO:0033840
nodes.Name: alpha-1,4-glucan glucosyltransferase (NDP-glucose donor) activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: [(1->4)-alpha-D-glucosyl](n) + an NDP-alpha-D-glucose = [(1->4)-alpha-D-glucosyl](n+1) + a ribonucleoside 5'-diphosphate + H+, where NDP is ADP or UDP.

nodes.label: GO:0071625
nodes.Name: vocalization behavior
nodes.Definition: The behavior in which an organism produces sounds by a mechanism involving its respiratory system.

nodes.label: GO:0098583
nodes.Name: learned vocalization behavior
nodes.Definition: A vocalization behavior that is the result of learning.

nodes.label: GO:0019645
nodes.Name: anaerobic electron transport chain
nodes.Definition: A process in which a series of electron carriers operate together to transfer electrons from donors such as NADH and FADH2 to any of several different terminal electron acceptors other than oxygen to generate a transmembrane electrochemical gradient.

nodes.label: GO:0018995
nodes.Name: host cellular component
nodes.Definition: Any cellular component of a host cell. The host is an organism in which another organism, for instance a parasite or symbiont, spends part or all of its life cycle and from which it obtains nourishment and/or protection.

nodes.label: GO:0044215
nodes.Name: obsolete other organism
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. A secondary organism with which the first organism is interacting.

nodes.label: GO:0009651
nodes.Name: response to salt stress
nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating an increase or decrease in the concentration of salt (particularly but not exclusively sodium and chloride ions) in the environment.

nodes.label: GO:0072342
nodes.Name: response to anion stress
nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of anion stress, an increase or decrease in the concentration of negatively charged ions in the environment.

nodes.label: GO:0010018
nodes.Name: far-red light signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: The series of molecular signals initiated upon sensing of far red light by a photoreceptor molecule. Far red light is electromagnetic radiation of wavelength 700-800nm. An example of this response is seen at the beginning of many plant species developmental stages. These include germination, and the point when cotyledon expansion is triggered. In certain species these processes take place in response to absorption of red light by the pigment molecule phytochrome, but the signal can be reversed by exposure to far red light. During the initial phase the phytochrome molecule is only present in the red light absorbing form, but on absorption of red light it changes to a far red light absorbing form, triggering progress through development. An immediate short period of exposure to far red light entirely returns the pigment to its initial state and prevents triggering of the developmental process. A thirty minute break between red and subsequent far red light exposure renders the red light effect irreversible, and development then occurs regardless of whether far red light exposure subsequently occurs.

Red light is electromagnetic radiation of wavelength of 580-700nm. Far red light is electromagnetic radiation of wavelength 700-800nm. An example of this response is seen at the beginning of many plant species developmental stages. These include germination, and the point when cotyledon expansion is triggered. In certain species these processes take place in response to absorption of red light by the pigment molecule phytochrome, but the signal can be reversed by exposure to far red light. During the initial phase the phytochrome molecule is only present in the red light absorbing form, but on absorption of red light it changes to a far red light absorbing form, triggering progress through development. An immediate short period of exposure to far red light entirely returns the pigment to its initial state and prevents triggering of the developmental process. A thirty minute break between red and subsequent far red light exposure renders the red light effect irreversible, and development then occurs regardless of whether far red light exposure subsequently occurs.

nodes.label: GO:0071488
nodes.Name: cellular response to very low light intensity stimulus
nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a very low light intensity stimulus. A very low light intensity stimulus is defined as a level of electromagnetic radiation below 0.001 mmol/m2/sec.

nodes.label: GO:0016048

nodes.label: GO:0051400
nodes.Name: BH domain binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to a Bcl-2 homology (BH) protein domain. Bcl-2-related proteins share homology in one to four conserved regions designated the Bcl-2 homology (BH) domains BH1, BH2, BH3 and BH4. These domains contribute at multiple levels to the function of these proteins in cell death and survival. Anti-apoptotic members of the Bcl-2 family have four BH domains (BH1-BH4). Pro-apoptotic members have fewer BH domains.

nodes.label: GO:0051432
nodes.Name: BH1 domain binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to a BH1 protein domain, present in Bcl-2 family members. Proteins that act as inhibitors of apoptosis harbour at least three BH domains: BH1, BH2 and BH3; the BH1 and BH2 domains are found in all death antagonists of the Bcl-2 family but only in one class of death agonists.

nodes.label: GO:0043694

nodes.label: GO:2000175

nodes.label: GO:0055131
nodes.Name: C3HC4-type RING finger domain binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to a C3HC4-type zinc finger domain of a protein. The C3HC4-type zinc finger is a variant of RING finger, is a cysteine-rich domain of 40 to 60 residues that coordinates two zinc ions, and has the consensus sequence: C-X2-C-X(9-39)-C-X(1-3)-H-X(2-3)-C-X2-C-X(4-48)-C-X2-C, where X is any amino acid. Many proteins containing a C3HC4-type RING finger play a key role in the ubiquitination pathway.

nodes.label: GO:0035914
nodes.Name: skeletal muscle cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a skeletal muscle cell, a somatic cell located in skeletal muscle.

nodes.label: GO:0075018

nodes.label: GO:0048070

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: bisdiphospho-1D-myo-inositol tetrakisphosphate + H2O = diphospho-1D-myo-inositol pentakisphosphate + phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0010244
nodes.Name: response to low fluence blue light stimulus by blue low-fluence system
nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of the detection of a low fluence blue light stimulus by the blue low-fluence system. Blue light is electromagnetic radiation with a wavelength of between 440 and 500nm. The blue low-fluence system responds to blue light at or below 0.1 micromols/m2. In certain species excitation of the blue low fluence system induces the transcription of a number of nuclear and plastid coded genes.

nodes.label: GO:0090200

nodes.label: GO:0016833

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the cleavage of a C-C bond by other means than by hydrolysis or oxidation, of a 3-hydroxy acid.

nodes.label: GO:0034830

nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: (2Z)-2,4-dihydroxydec-2-enedioate = pyruvate + 7-oxoheptanoate.

nodes.label: GO:0046820

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: L-glutamine + chorismate = 4-amino-4-deoxychorismate + L-glutamate. It is composed of two enzymatic activities (which may be present on one or two polypeptides); the first is a glutaminase which yields ammonia from glutamine, releasing glutamate. The ammonia is used by the second activity which catalyzes the amination of chorismate to form 4-amino-4-deoxychorismate.

nodes.label: GO:0008051

nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. A complex that possesses farnesyl-diphosphate farnesyl transferase activity.

nodes.Definition: Binds to and modulates the activity of a protein phosphatase.

nodes.Definition: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of the red or far-red signaling pathway, the series of molecular signals initiated upon sensing by photoreceptor molecules of red light or far red light.

nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the release of an N-terminal amino acid, preferably a neutral or hydrophobic one, from a polypeptide. Aminoacyl-arylamides are poor substrates.

nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a light stimulus, electromagnetic radiation of wavelengths classified as infrared, visible or ultraviolet light.

Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter as a result of detection of, or exposure to, a decrease in the concentration of salt (particularly but not exclusively sodium and chloride ions) in the environment.

nodes.label: GO:0044139

nodes.label: GO:0075305

nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Any process by which the symbiont regulates the increase in its size or mass, or its progression from an initial condition to a later condition, on or near the cells or tissues of the host organism.

nodes.label: GO:0033916

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a ubiquitin-like from one protein to another via the reaction X-ULP + Y = Y-ULP + X, where both X-ULP and Y-ULP are covalent linkages. ULP represents a ubiquitin-like protein.

nodes.Definition: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of high-density lipoprotein particle clearance. nodes.label: GO:0010986
nodes.Name: positive regulation of lipoprotein particle clearance
nodes.Definition: Any process that increases the rate, frequency, or extent of lipoprotein particle clearance. Lipoprotein particle clearance is the process in which a lipoprotein particle is removed from the blood via receptor-mediated endocytosis and its constituent parts degraded.

nodes.label: GO:0009703
nodes.Name: nitrate reductase (NADH) activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: nitrite + NAD+ + H2O = nitrate + NADH + H+.

nodes.label: GO:1902108

nodes.Definition: Any regulation of mitochondrial membrane permeability that is involved in apoptotic process.

nodes.label: GO:1902109
nodes.Name: negative regulation of mitochondrial membrane permeability involved in apoptotic process
nodes.Definition: Any negative regulation of mitochondrial membrane permeability that is involved in apoptotic process.

nodes.label: GO:0014902
nodes.Name: myotube differentiation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a myotube cell. Myotube differentiation starts with myoblast fusion and the appearance of specific cell markers (this is the cell development step). Then individual myotubes can fuse to form bigger myotubes and start to contract. Myotubes are multinucleated cells that are formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.

nodes.label: GO:0090162

nodes.Definition: The specification and formation of anisotropic intracellular organization of an epithelial cell.

nodes.label: GO:1902220

nodes.label: GO:0038147

nodes.label: GO:0036018

nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an erythropoietin stimulus.

nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cytokine stimulus.

nodes.label: GO:1904059

nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of locomotor rhythm.

nodes.label: GO:1904060
nodes.Name: negative regulation of locomotor rhythm

nodes.Definition: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a filament composed of myosin molecules.

nodes.label: GO:0071688

nodes.Definition: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins to form the myosin-based thick filaments of myofibrils in striated muscle.

nodes.label: GO:0035740

nodes.label: GO:1901944

nodes.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving miltiradiene.

nodes.label: GO:0000023
nodes.Name: maltose metabolic process
nodes.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving the disaccharide maltose (4-O-alpha-D-glucopyranosyl-D-glucopyranose), an intermediate in the catabolism of glycogen and starch.

nodes.label: GO:0005984
nodes.Name: disaccharide metabolic process
nodes.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving any disaccharide, sugars composed of two monosaccharide units.

nodes.label: GO:0014904
nodes.Name: myotube cell development
nodes.Definition: The process aimed at the progression of a myotube cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell. Myotubes are multinucleated cells that are formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.

nodes.label: GO:0035935
nodes.Name: androgen secretion
nodes.Definition: The regulated release of an androgen into the circulatory system. Androgens are steroid hormones that stimulate or control the development and maintenance of masculine characteristics in vertebrates.

nodes.label: GO:0035942
