nodes.Definition: The regulated release of dehydroepiandrosterone (3beta-hydroxyandrost-5-en-17-one) into the circulatory system.

nodes.label: GO:0007015
nodes.Name: actin filament organization
nodes.Definition: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising actin filaments. Includes processes that control the spatial distribution of actin filaments, such as organizing filaments into meshworks, bundles, or other structures, as by cross-linking.

nodes.label: GO:0071691
nodes.Name: cardiac muscle thin filament assembly
nodes.Definition: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins to form the actin-based thin filaments of myofibrils in cardiac muscle.

nodes.label: GO:0030840
nodes.Name: negative regulation of intermediate filament polymerization
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of intermediate filament polymerization.

nodes.label: GO:0045107
nodes.Name: intermediate filament polymerization
nodes.Definition: Assembly of intermediate filaments by the addition of component monomers to a filament. Polymerization of intermediate filament proteins results from interactions among several distinct binding sites on the constituent proteins. Nuclear lamin head-to-tail polymers arise from one such interaction. Deletion analysis localized the binding sites to the ends of the rod domain that are highly conserved among all intermediate filament proteins. Data indicate that one type of interaction in intermediate filament protein polymerization is the longitudinal binding of dimers via the conserved end segments of the coiled-coil rod domain.

nodes.label: GO:0044116
nodes.Name: biological process involved in interaction with host
nodes.Definition: An interaction between two organisms living together in more or less intimate association. The term host is used for the larger (macro) of the two members of a symbiosis; the various forms of symbiosis include parasitism, commensalism and mutualism.

nodes.label: GO:0044146
nodes.Name: obsolete negative regulation of growth of symbiont involved in interaction with host
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the increase in size or mass of an organism occurring in, on or near the exterior of its host organism.

nodes.label: GO:0014887
nodes.Name: cardiac muscle adaptation
nodes.Definition: The process in which cardiac muscle adapts, with consequent modifications to structural and/or functional phenotypes, in response to a stimulus. Stimuli include contractile activity, loading conditions, substrate supply, and environmental factors.

nodes.label: GO:0014899
nodes.Name: cardiac muscle atrophy
nodes.Definition: A process, occurring in the heart, in which a decrease in cell mass and then in heart size occurs due to shrinking of the individual cells. The shrinkage is caused by protein degradation.

nodes.label: GO:2000526
nodes.Name: positive regulation of glycoprotein biosynthetic process involved in immunological synapse formation
nodes.Definition: Any positive regulation of glycoprotein biosynthetic process that is involved in immunological synapse formation.

nodes.label: GO:0045590
nodes.Name: negative regulation of regulatory T cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the rate of differentiation of regulatory T cells.

nodes.label: GO:0034845
nodes.Name: obsolete naphthyl-2-methyl-succinyl-CoA dehydrogenase activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: naphthyl-2-methyl-succinyl-CoA = naphthyl-2-methylene-succinyl-CoA + 2 H+ + 2 e-.

nodes.label: GO:0051828
nodes.Name: symbiont entry into host
nodes.Definition: Entry of a symbiont into the body, tissues, or cells of a host organism as part of the symbiont life cycle. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0051829
nodes.Name: obsolete entry into host through natural portals
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Penetration by a symbiont into a host organism via naturally occurring openings in the host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0070997
nodes.Name: obsolete neuron death
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. The process of cell death in a neuron.

nodes.label: GO:1901214
nodes.Name: obsolete regulation of neuron death
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of neuron death.

nodes.label: GO:0044120
nodes.Name: obsolete development of symbiont in host vacuole
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. The progression of the symbiont from an initial condition to a later condition, occurring in a host vacuole. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0075066
nodes.Name: obsolete growth or development of symbiont in host organelle
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. The increase in size or mass of symbiont, or the progression of the symbiont from an initial condition to a later condition, occurring in its host's organelle. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0001960
nodes.Name: negative regulation of cytokine-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the cytokine mediated signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:0080048
nodes.Name: GDP-D-glucose phosphorylase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: GDP-alpha-D-glucose + phosphate = alpha-D-glucose-1-phosphate + GDP.

nodes.label: GO:0007612
nodes.Name: learning
nodes.Definition: Any process in an organism in which a relatively long-lasting adaptive behavioral change occurs as the result of experience.

nodes.label: GO:0098597
nodes.Name: observational learning
nodes.Definition: Learning that occurs through observing the behavior of others.

nodes.label: GO:0014730
nodes.Name: skeletal muscle regeneration at neuromuscular junction
nodes.Definition: The regrowth of muscle tissue to repair injured or damaged muscle fibers in the postnatal stage at the neuromuscular junction. Regeneration of neuromuscular junctions occurs in an orderly way and relies on communication between nerve and muscle. Skeletal myofibers regenerate after injury and form neuro-muscular junctions with motor axons similar to normal ones. Regenerating myofibers develop within the basal lamina sheaths (satellite cells) of original myofibers.

nodes.label: GO:0051721
nodes.Name: protein phosphatase 2A binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to protein phosphatase 2A.

nodes.label: GO:0050941
nodes.Name: negative regulation of pigment cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of pigment cell differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:0050943
nodes.Name: negative regulation of iridophore differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of iridophore differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:0047693
nodes.Name: ATP diphosphatase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = AMP + H+ + diphosphate.

nodes.label: GO:1990313
nodes.Name: type-III cohesin domain binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to a type-III cohesin domain of a protein. Type-III cohesin domain is the binding partner of type-III dockerin domain.

nodes.label: GO:0035899
nodes.Name: suppression of blood coagulation in another organism
nodes.Definition: Any process in which an organism stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of blood coagulation in another organism. Blood coagulation is the sequential process in which the multiple coagulation factors of the blood interact, ultimately resulting in the formation of an insoluble fibrin clot.

nodes.label: GO:0044470
nodes.Name: envenomation resulting in negative regulation of blood coagulation in another organism
nodes.Definition: A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the resultant stopping, prevention or reduction in the frequency, rate or extent of blood coagulation in the bitten organism.

nodes.label: GO:0019512
nodes.Name: lactose catabolic process via tagatose-6-phosphate
nodes.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of lactose, via the intermediate tagatose-6-phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0102006
nodes.Name: obsolete 4-methyl-2-oxopentanoate dehydrogenase activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: 4-methyl-2-oxopentanoate + coenzyme A(4-) + NAD(1-) = isovaleryl-CoA(4-) + carbon dioxide + NADH(2-).

nodes.label: GO:0004827
nodes.Name: proline-tRNA ligase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + L-proline + tRNA(Pro) = AMP + diphosphate + L-prolyl-tRNA(Pro).

nodes.label: GO:0002145
nodes.Name: 4-amino-5-hydroxymethyl-2-methylpyrimidine diphosphatase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: 4-amino-5-hydroxymethyl-2-methylpyrimidine pyrophosphate + H2O = hydroxymethylpyrimidine phosphate + phosphate + H+.

nodes.label: GO:0045661
nodes.Name: regulation of myoblast differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of myoblast differentiation. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

nodes.label: GO:2000690
nodes.Name: regulation of cardiac muscle cell myoblast differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle cell myoblast differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:0006470
nodes.Name: protein dephosphorylation
nodes.Definition: The process of removing one or more phosphoric residues from a protein.

nodes.label: GO:0070940
nodes.Name: obsolete dephosphorylation of RNA polymerase II C-terminal domain
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. The process of removing a phosphate group from an amino acid residue in the C-terminal domain of RNA polymerase II. Some dephosphorylation occurs during transcription while some may occur after the enzyme is released from the template in order to prepare it for the beginning of the transcription cycle again. RNA polymerase II with little or no phosphorylation is referred to as the hypophosphorylated or II(A) form.

nodes.label: GO:0052891
nodes.Name: aliphatic (S)-hydroxynitrile lyase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: an aliphatic (S)-hydroxynitrile = an aliphatic aldehyde or ketone + cyanide.

nodes.label: GO:0007605
nodes.Name: sensory perception of sound
nodes.Definition: The series of events required for an organism to receive an auditory stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. Sonic stimuli are detected in the form of vibrations and are processed to form a sound.

nodes.label: GO:0050910
nodes.Name: detection of mechanical stimulus involved in sensory perception of sound
nodes.Definition: The series of events involved in the perception of sound vibration in which the vibration is received and converted into a molecular signal.

nodes.label: GO:0097202
nodes.Name: activation of cysteine-type endopeptidase activity
nodes.Definition: Any process that initiates the activity of the inactive enzyme cysteine-type endopeptidase.

nodes.label: GO:0044118
nodes.Name: obsolete development of symbiont in host cell
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. The progression of the symbiont from an initial condition to a later condition, occurring in its host's cell. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0052094
nodes.Name: formation of haustorium for nutrient acquisition
nodes.Definition: The assembly of a haustorium, a projection from a symbiotic cell or tissue that penetrates the host's tissues for the purpose of obtaining nutrients. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0015924
nodes.Name: mannosyl-oligosaccharide mannosidase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of the terminal alpha-D-mannose residues in oligo-mannose oligosaccharides.

nodes.label: GO:0052767
nodes.Name: mannosyl-oligosaccharide 1,6-alpha-mannosidase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of the alpha-(1->6) bonds of alpha-D-mannose residues in mannosyl-oligosaccharide.

nodes.label: GO:0004183
nodes.Name: obsolete carboxypeptidase E activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: peptidyl-L-lysine (or peptidyl-L-arginine) + H2O = peptide + L-lysine (or L-arginine). Function is activated by Co2+ and inhibited by 1,10-phenanthroline and other chelating agents.

nodes.label: GO:0045635
nodes.Name: negative regulation of melanocyte differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of melanocyte differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:0050949
nodes.Name: negative regulation of late stripe melanocyte differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of late stripe melanocyte differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:0035995
nodes.Name: detection of muscle stretch
nodes.Definition: The series of events by which a muscle stretch stimulus is received by a cell and converted into a molecular signal.

nodes.label: GO:0055004
nodes.Name: atrial cardiac myofibril assembly
nodes.Definition: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the atrial cardiac myofibril over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A cardiac myofibril is a myofibril specific to cardiac muscle cells.

nodes.label: GO:0070380
nodes.Name: high mobility group box 1 receptor activity
nodes.Definition: Combining with high mobility group box 1 (HMBGB1) and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.

nodes.label: GO:0018524
nodes.Name: obsolete acetophenone carboxylase activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: acetophenone + CO2 = H+ + benzoyl acetate.

nodes.label: GO:0075187
nodes.Name: hyphopodium formation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a specialized structure, consisted of stalked, thick-walled, lobed cells of vegetative epiphytic hyphae, is formed, to attach and penetrate the host surface. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0075188
nodes.Name: regulation of hyphopodium formation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of symbiont hyphopodium formation on or near its host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0002075
nodes.Name: somitomeric trunk muscle development
nodes.Definition: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the somitomeric trunk muscle over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The somitomeric trunk muscle is derived from somitomeric mesoderm. The muscle begins its development with the differentiation of the muscle cells and ends with the mature muscle. An example of this process is found in Mus musculus.

nodes.label: GO:0014708
nodes.Name: regulation of somitomeric trunk muscle development
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of somitomeric trunk muscle development.

nodes.label: GO:0008805
nodes.Name: carbon-monoxide oxygenase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: CO + H2O + ferrocytochrome b-561 = CO2 + 2 H+ + 2 ferricytochrome b-561.

nodes.label: GO:0047767
nodes.Name: carbon-monoxide oxygenase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: CO + H2O + ferrocytochrome b-561 = CO2 + 2 H+ + 2 ferricytochrome b-561.

nodes.label: GO:0055026
nodes.Name: negative regulation of cardiac muscle tissue development
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle tissue development.

nodes.label: GO:0004446
nodes.Name: inositol-hexakisphosphate phosphatase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: myo-inositol hexakisphosphate + H2O = myo-inositol pentakisphosphate (mixed isomers) + phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0071754
nodes.Name: IgM immunoglobulin complex, circulating
nodes.Definition: A polymer of five or six IgM core units each composed of two identical immunoglobulin heavy chains of the IgM isotype and two identical immunoglobulin light chains, held together by disulfide bonds; the individual IgM core units are held together via disulfide bonds with a single J chain polypeptide acting as a bridge between two of the polymeric units. Circulating IgM is present in the extracellular space, in mucosal areas or other tissues, or in the blood or lymph.

nodes.label: GO:0071757
nodes.Name: hexameric IgM immunoglobulin complex
nodes.Definition: A circulating form of IgM consisting of a hexamer of IgM core units with a single J chain polypeptide.

nodes.label: GO:0098758
nodes.Name: response to interleukin-8
nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-8 stimulus.

nodes.label: GO:0032859
nodes.Name: activation of GTPase activity
nodes.Definition: Any process that initiates the activity of an inactive GTPase through the replacement of GDP by GTP.

nodes.label: GO:0090630
nodes.Name: activation of GTPase activity
nodes.Definition: Any process that initiates the activity of an inactive GTPase through the replacement of GDP by GTP.

nodes.label: GO:0004830
nodes.Name: tryptophan-tRNA ligase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + L-tryptophan + tRNA(Trp) = AMP + diphosphate + L-tryptophanyl-tRNA(Trp).

nodes.label: GO:1904036
nodes.Name: negative regulation of epithelial cell apoptotic process
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of epithelial cell apoptotic process.

nodes.label: GO:0004208
nodes.Name: obsolete caspase-3 activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the cleavage at the terminal bond of the motif: Asp-Xaa-Xaa-Asp-Xaa. Enzymes with this function are members of the peptidase family C14 and they appear to function in the inactivation of proteins involved in cellular repair and homeostasis during the effector stage of apoptosis.

nodes.label: GO:0103077
nodes.Name: obsolete quercetin 3-glucoside 7-O-rhamnosyltransferase activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: quercetin-3-glucoside + UDP-L-rhamnose = quercetin-3-O-glucoside-7-O-rhamnoside + UDP.

nodes.label: GO:0075053
nodes.Name: penetration peg formation
nodes.Definition: The assembly by the symbiont of a peg-like structure for the purpose of penetration into its host organism, which penetrates through the host cuticle and epidermal cell wall. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0030275
nodes.Name: LRR domain binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to a LRR domain (leucine rich repeats) of a protein.

nodes.label: GO:0008220
nodes.Name: obsolete necrosis
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. The processes that cause necrosis, the death of tissues, in another organism.

nodes.label: GO:0070265
nodes.Name: obsolete necrotic cell death
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. A type of cell death that is morphologically characterized by an increasingly translucent cytoplasm, swelling of organelles, minor ultrastructural modifications of the nucleus (specifically, dilatation of the nuclear membrane and condensation of chromatin into small, irregular, circumscribed patches) and increased cell volume (oncosis), culminating in the disruption of the plasma membrane and subsequent loss of intracellular contents. Necrotic cells do not fragment into discrete corpses as their apoptotic counterparts do. Moreover, their nuclei remain intact and can aggregate and accumulate in necrotic tissues.

nodes.label: GO:0033931
nodes.Name: endogalactosaminidase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the endohydrolysis of (1->4)-alpha-D-galactosaminidic linkages in poly(D-galactosamine).

nodes.label: GO:0052757
nodes.Name: chondroitin hydrolase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of hexosaminic linkages in chondroitin, a linear polymer structure composed of the repeating disaccharide unit [->4)-D-glucuronic acid-(1->3)-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine-(1-], also written as [->4GlcUA1->3GalNAc1-].

nodes.label: GO:0051136
nodes.Name: regulation of NK T cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of natural killer T cell differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:0020003
nodes.Name: symbiont-containing vacuole
nodes.Definition: Membrane-bounded vacuole within a host cell in which a symbiont organism resides. The vacuole membrane is derived from both the host and symbiont.

nodes.label: GO:0020004
nodes.Name: symbiont-containing vacuolar space
nodes.Definition: The space between a symbiont plasma membrane and the symbiont-containing vacuole membrane.

nodes.label: GO:0047483
nodes.Name: imidazoleacetate-phosphoribosyldiphosphate ligase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: 5-phospho-alpha-D-ribose 1-diphosphate + ATP + H2O + imidazol-4-ylacetate = 1-(5-phosphoribosyl)imidazol-4-ylacetate + ADP + diphosphate + 2 H+ + phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0032462
nodes.Name: regulation of protein homooligomerization
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein homooligomerization.

nodes.label: GO:1901093
nodes.Name: regulation of protein homotetramerization
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein homotetramerization.

nodes.label: GO:1905064
nodes.Name: negative regulation of vascular associated smooth muscle cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of vascular smooth muscle cell differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:0050562
nodes.Name: obsolete lysine-tRNA(Pyl) ligase activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: tRNA(Pyl) + L-lysine + ATP = L-lysyl-tRNA(Pyl) + diphosphate + AMP.

nodes.label: GO:0075315
nodes.Name: positive regulation of basidium development
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of basidium development, a process that leads to the formation of basidium, a small, specialized club-shaped structure typically bearing four basidiospores at the tips of minute projections. The basidium is unique to basidiomycetes and distinguishes them from other kinds of fungi.

nodes.label: GO:1903038
nodes.Name: negative regulation of leukocyte cell-cell adhesion
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of leukocyte cell-cell adhesion.

nodes.label: GO:0050267
nodes.Name: rubber cis-polyprenylcistransferase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: (cis-prenyl)n-diphosphate + isopentenyl diphosphate = (cis-prenyl)(n+1)-diphosphate + diphosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0004869
nodes.Name: cysteine-type endopeptidase inhibitor activity
nodes.Definition: Binds to and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a cysteine-type endopeptidase.

nodes.label: GO:0010859
nodes.Name: calcium-dependent cysteine-type endopeptidase inhibitor activity
nodes.Definition: Binds to and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a calcium-dependent cysteine-type endopeptidase, any enzyme that hydrolyzes peptide bonds in polypeptides by a mechanism in which the sulfhydryl group of a cysteine residue at the active center acts as a nucleophile in a calcium-dependent manner.

nodes.label: GO:0044553
nodes.Name: modulation of biological quality in another organism
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a biological quality in another organism. A biological quality is a measurable attribute of an organism or part of an organism, such as size, mass, shape, color, etc.

nodes.label: GO:0048073
nodes.Name: regulation of eye pigmentation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of establishment of a pattern of pigment in the eye of an organism.

nodes.label: GO:0048076
nodes.Name: regulation of compound eye pigmentation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of establishment of a pattern of pigment in the compound eye.

nodes.label: GO:0010616
nodes.Name: negative regulation of cardiac muscle adaptation
nodes.Definition: Any process that decreases the rate, extent or frequency of the process in which cardiac muscle adapts, with consequent modifications to structural and/or functional phenotypes, in response to a stimulus. Stimuli include contractile activity, loading conditions, substrate supply, and environmental factors.

nodes.label: GO:0047035
nodes.Name: testosterone dehydrogenase (NAD+) activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: testosterone + NAD+ = androst-4-ene-3,17-dione + NADH.

nodes.label: GO:0050327
nodes.Name: testosterone dehydrogenase (NAD+) activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: testosterone + NAD+ = androst-4-ene-3,17-dione + NADH.

nodes.label: GO:0080069
nodes.Name: 7-methylthioheptyl-desulfoglucosinolate sulfotransferase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: 7-methylthioheptyl-desulfoglucosinolate + 3'-phosphoadenosine 5'-phosphosulfate = 7-methylthioheptyl-glucosinolate + adenosine 3',5'-bisphosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0046634
nodes.Name: regulation of alpha-beta T cell activation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of alpha-beta T cell activation.

nodes.label: GO:0038058
nodes.Name: obsolete TNFSF11 receptor activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Combining with a tumor necrosis factor ligand superfamily member 11 (TNFSF11) and transmitting the signal across the cell membrane to initiate a change in cell activity or function.

nodes.label: GO:0071847
nodes.Name: obsolete TNFSF11-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. The series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of tumor necrosis factor ligand superfamily member 11 (TNFSF11) to its receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.label: GO:0034242
nodes.Name: negative regulation of syncytium formation by plasma membrane fusion
nodes.Definition: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the formation of a syncytium, a mass of cytoplasm containing several nuclei enclosed within a single plasma membrane, by the fusion of the plasma membranes of two or more individual cells.

nodes.label: GO:1904037
nodes.Name: positive regulation of epithelial cell apoptotic process
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of epithelial cell apoptotic process.

nodes.label: GO:0004226
nodes.Name: obsolete Gly-X carboxypeptidase activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: peptidyl-Gly-Xaa + H2O = peptidyl-Gly + Xaa.

nodes.label: GO:0042000
nodes.Name: translocation of peptides or proteins into host
nodes.Definition: The directed movement of peptides or proteins produced by an organism to a location inside its host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0044417
nodes.Name: translocation of molecules into host
nodes.Definition: The directed movement of a molecule(s) produced by an organism to a location inside its host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0002362
nodes.Name: CD4-positive, CD25-positive, alpha-beta regulatory T cell lineage commitment
nodes.Definition: The process in which a CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell becomes committed to becoming a CD4-positive, CD25-positive, alpha-beta regulatory T cell.

nodes.label: GO:0043373
nodes.Name: CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell lineage commitment
nodes.Definition: The process in which an immature T cell becomes committed to becoming a CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell.

nodes.label: GO:0046958
nodes.Name: nonassociative learning
nodes.Definition: A simple form of learning whereby the repeated presence of a stimulus leads to a change in the probability or strength of the response to that stimulus. There is no association of one type of stimulus with another, rather it is a generalized response to the environment.

nodes.label: GO:0046959
nodes.Name: habituation
nodes.Definition: A decrease in a behavioral response to a repeated stimulus. This is exemplified by the failure of a person to show a startle response to a loud noise that has been repeatedly presented.

nodes.label: GO:0071492
nodes.Name: cellular response to UV-A
nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a UV-A radiation stimulus. UV-A radiation (UV-A light) spans the wavelengths 315 to 400 nm.

nodes.label: GO:0044632
nodes.Name: obsolete negative regulation of complement activation, lectin pathway in another organism
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the rate of complement activation by the lectin pathway, in a different organism.

nodes.label: GO:0044640
nodes.Name: obsolete envenomation resulting in negative regulation of complement activation, lectin pathway in another organism
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. A process that begins with venom being forced into an organism by the bite or sting of another organism, and ends with the resultant negative regulation of complement activation via the lectin pathway in the bitten/stung organism.

nodes.label: GO:0044369
nodes.Name: feeding behavior
nodes.Definition: Behavior associated with the intake of food.

nodes.label: GO:0051693
nodes.Name: actin filament capping
nodes.Definition: The binding of a protein or protein complex to the end of an actin filament, thus preventing the addition, exchange or removal of further actin subunits.

nodes.label: GO:0009644
nodes.Name: response to high light intensity
nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a high light intensity stimulus.

nodes.label: GO:0055121
nodes.Name: response to high fluence blue light stimulus by blue high-fluence system
nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of the detection of a high fluence blue light stimulus by the blue high-fluence system. Blue light is electromagnetic radiation with a wavelength of between 440 and 500nm. The blue high-fluence system responds to blue light at levels between 100 and 1000 micromols/m2.

nodes.label: GO:0060337
nodes.Name: type I interferon-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: The series of molecular signals initiated by type I interferon binding to its receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription. Type I interferons include the interferon-alpha, beta, delta, episilon, zeta, kappa, tau, and omega gene families.

nodes.label: GO:0102582
nodes.Name: cyanidin 3-O-p-coumaroylglucoside 2-O''-xylosyltransferase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: cyanidin 3-O-(6-O-(E)-4-coumaroyl-beta-D-glucoside) + UDP-alpha-D-xylose = cyanidin 3-O-[2''-O-xylosyl) 6''-O-(p-coumaroyl) glucoside + UDP + H+.

nodes.label: GO:1904157
nodes.Name: DN4 thymocyte differentiation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized features of a DN4 thymocyte. A DN4 thymocyte is a CD4-,CD8- thymocyte that is also CD44-,CD25-.

nodes.label: GO:0090075
nodes.Name: relaxation of muscle
nodes.Definition: A process in which the extent of muscle contraction is reduced. Muscle relaxation can involve a number of processes including the removal of calcium from the cytoplasm to the sarcoplasmic reticulum lumen through the action of Ca2+ ATPases. In some muscles, calcium-independent pathways also play a role in muscle relaxation by decreasing the phosphorylation state of myosin light chain.

nodes.label: GO:0090076
nodes.Name: relaxation of skeletal muscle
nodes.Definition: A process in which the extent of skeletal muscle tissue contraction is reduced. Muscle relaxation involves the removal of calcium from the cytoplasm to the sarcoplasmic reticulum lumen through the action of Ca2+ ATPases.

nodes.label: GO:0030833
nodes.Name: regulation of actin filament polymerization
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly of actin filaments by the addition of actin monomers to a filament.

nodes.label: GO:2000561
nodes.Name: regulation of CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell proliferation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell proliferation.

nodes.label: GO:0046637
nodes.Name: regulation of alpha-beta T cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of alpha-beta T cell differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:0019233
nodes.Name: sensory perception of pain
nodes.Definition: The series of events required for an organism to receive a painful stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. Pain is medically defined as the physical sensation of discomfort or distress caused by injury or illness, so can hence be described as a harmful stimulus which signals current (or impending) tissue damage. Pain may come from extremes of temperature, mechanical damage, electricity or from noxious chemical substances. This is a neurological process.

nodes.label: GO:1990497
nodes.Name: regulation of cytoplasmic translation in response to stress
nodes.Definition: Modulation of the frequency, rate or extent of cytoplasmic translation as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress. The stress is usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).

nodes.label: GO:1990611
nodes.Name: regulation of cytoplasmic translational initiation in response to stress
nodes.Definition: Modulation of the frequency, rate or extent of cytoplasmic translational initiation as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress. The stress is usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).

nodes.label: GO:2000831
nodes.Name: regulation of steroid hormone secretion
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of steroid hormone secretion.

nodes.label: GO:0048315
nodes.Name: conidium formation
nodes.Definition: The process of producing non-motile spores, called conidia, via mitotic asexual reproduction in higher fungi. Conidia are haploid cells genetically identical to their haploid parent. They are produced by conversion of hyphal elements, or are borne on sporogenous cells on or within specialized structures termed conidiophores, and participate in dispersal of the fungus.

nodes.label: GO:0075306
nodes.Name: regulation of conidium formation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of conidium formation, a process of producing non-motile spores, called conidia, via mitotic asexual reproduction in higher fungi. Conidia are haploid cells genetically identical to their haploid parent. They are produced by conversion of hyphal elements, or are borne on sporogenous cells on or within specialized structures termed conidiophores, and participate in dispersal of the fungus.

nodes.label: GO:0010803
nodes.Name: regulation of tumor necrosis factor-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the rate or extent of the tumor necrosis factor-mediated signaling pathway. The tumor necrosis factor-mediated signaling pathway is the series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of tumor necrosis factor binding to a cell surface receptor.

nodes.label: GO:1903265
nodes.Name: positive regulation of tumor necrosis factor-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of tumor necrosis factor-mediated signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:0004479

nodes.label: GO:1903746

nodes.label: GO:0099621

nodes.label: GO:0060949

nodes.label: GO:0060985
nodes.Name: epicardium-derived cardiac vascular smooth muscle cell fate commitment
nodes.Definition: The commitment of an epicardial cell to a cardiac vascular smooth muscle cell fate and its capacity to differentiate into a cardiac vascular smooth muscle cell.

nodes.label: GO:0019781

nodes.label: GO:0019944
nodes.Name: NEDD8 activating enzyme activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the initiation of the NEDD8 (RUB1) conjugation cascade.

nodes.label: GO:0075045
nodes.Name: regulation of formation by symbiont of haustorium for nutrient acquisition from host
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of symbiont haustorium formation for nutrient acquisition from host. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0075046
nodes.Name: positive regulation of formation by symbiont of haustorium for nutrient acquisition from host
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of symbiont haustorium formation for nutrient acquisition from host. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0035929
nodes.Name: steroid hormone secretion
nodes.Definition: The regulated release of any steroid that acts as a hormone into the circulatory system.

nodes.label: GO:0035930
nodes.Name: corticosteroid hormone secretion
nodes.Definition: The regulated release of any corticosteroid hormone into the circulatory system.

nodes.label: GO:0071749
nodes.Name: polymeric IgA immunoglobulin complex
nodes.Definition: A protein complex composed of two, three, or four monomeric IgA immunoglobulin complexes linked through both direct disulfide bonds and through disulfide binded monomers of J chain acting as a bridge. Each IgA monomer consists of two identical immunoglobulin heavy chains of an IgA isotype and two identical immunoglobulin light chains, held together by disulfide bonds. Dimeric IgA is sometimes complexed additionally with secretory component, and present in the extracellular space, in mucosal areas or other tissues, or circulating in the blood or lymph.

nodes.label: GO:0071751
nodes.Name: secretory IgA immunoglobulin complex
nodes.Definition: A polymeric IgA immunoglobulin complex that is complexed with one chain of secretory component (SC). Polymeric IgA is present in mucosal areas, having been transported via a transcytosis mechanism in mucosal epithelial cells relying on the polymeric Ig receptor, a portion of which then remains bound to the polymeric IgA as secretory component.

nodes.label: GO:0014710
nodes.Name: negative regulation of somitomeric trunk muscle development
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of somitomeric trunk muscle development. The somitomeric trunk muscle is derived from somitomeric mesoderm. The muscle begins its development with the differentiation of the muscle cells and ends with the mature muscle.

nodes.label: GO:0002122
nodes.Name: fear-induced aggressive behavior
nodes.Definition: Aggressive behavior associated with attempts to flee from a threat.

nodes.label: GO:0004330
nodes.Name: fructose-2,6-bisphosphate 2-phosphatase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: D-fructose 2,6-bisphosphate + H2O = D-fructose-6-phosphate + phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0004331
nodes.Name: fructose-2,6-bisphosphate 2-phosphatase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: D-fructose 2,6-bisphosphate + H2O = D-fructose-6-phosphate + phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0060947
nodes.Name: cardiac vascular smooth muscle cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a cardiac vascular smooth muscle cell. A cardiac vascular smooth muscle cell covers the heart vasculature and lacks transverse striations in its constituent fibers.

nodes.label: GO:0004211
nodes.Name: obsolete caspase-9 activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. (Was not defined before being made obsolete).

nodes.label: GO:0003299
nodes.Name: muscle hypertrophy in response to stress
nodes.Definition: The enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of a muscle organ or tissue due to an increase in the size of its muscle cells as a result of a disturbance in organismal or cellular homeostasis.

nodes.label: GO:0043500
nodes.Name: muscle adaptation
nodes.Definition: A process in which muscle adapts, with consequent modifications to structural and/or functional phenotypes, in response to a stimulus. Stimuli include contractile activity, loading conditions, substrate supply, and environmental factors. These adaptive events occur in both muscle fibers and associated structures (motoneurons and capillaries), and they involve alterations in regulatory mechanisms, contractile properties and metabolic capacities.

nodes.label: GO:0016329
nodes.Name: obsolete apoptosis regulator activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. The function held by products which directly regulate any step in the process of apoptosis.

nodes.label: GO:0043757

nodes.label: GO:1904656
nodes.Name: regulation of sensory perception of sweet taste
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of sensory perception of sweet taste.

nodes.label: GO:0071358
nodes.Name: cellular response to type III interferon
nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a type III interferon stimulus. Interferon lambda is the only member of the type III interferon found so far.

nodes.label: GO:0047384
nodes.Name: [hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA reductase (NADPH)]-phosphatase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: H2O + [hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA reductase (NADPH)] phosphate = phosphate + [hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA reductase (NADPH)].

nodes.label: GO:0004789
nodes.Name: thiamine-phosphate diphosphorylase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: 4-amino-2-methyl-5-diphosphomethylpyrimidine + 4-methyl-5-(2-phosphoethyl)-thiazole + H+ = diphosphate + thiamine phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0016799

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of any N-glycosyl bond.

nodes.label: GO:1902214
nodes.Name: regulation of interleukin-4-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of interleukin-4-mediated signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:0008625
nodes.Name: extrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway via death domain receptors
nodes.Definition: The series of molecular signals in which a signal is conveyed from the cell surface to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway starts with a ligand binding to a death domain receptor on the cell surface, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

nodes.label: GO:1902042
nodes.Name: negative regulation of extrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway via death domain receptors
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of extrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway via death domain receptors.

nodes.label: GO:0075257
nodes.Name: positive regulation of teliospore formation
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of teliospore formation, which is the formation of a thick-walled resting or overwintering spore produced by the rust fungi (Uredinales) and smut fungi (Ustilaginales) in which karyogamy occurs.

nodes.label: GO:0044409
nodes.Name: symbiont entry into host
nodes.Definition: Entry of a symbiont into the body, tissues, or cells of a host organism as part of the symbiont life cycle. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0044410
nodes.Name: obsolete entry into host through natural portals
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Penetration by a symbiont into a host organism via naturally occurring openings in the host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0036495
nodes.Name: negative regulation of translation initiation in response to endoplasmic reticulum stress
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of translation initiation as a result of endoplasmic reticulum stress.

nodes.label: GO:0010984
nodes.Name: regulation of lipoprotein particle clearance
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of lipoprotein particle clearance. Lipoprotein particle clearance is the process in which a lipoprotein particle is removed from the blood via receptor-mediated endocytosis and its constituent parts degraded.

nodes.label: GO:0004588

nodes.label: GO:0016661

nodes.label: GO:0016662

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which a nitrogenous group, excluding NH and NH2 groups, acts as a hydrogen or electron donor and reduces a cytochrome.

nodes.label: GO:1901298
nodes.Name: regulation of hydrogen peroxide-mediated programmed cell death
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of hydrogen peroxide-mediated programmed cell death.

nodes.label: GO:1901299
nodes.Name: negative regulation of hydrogen peroxide-mediated programmed cell death
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of hydrogen peroxide-mediated programmed cell death.

nodes.label: GO:0047254

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: 2,4-dihydroxy-7-methoxy-2H-1,4-benzoxazin-3(4H)-one + UDP-D-glucose = 2,4-dihydroxy-7-methoxy-2H-1,4-benzoxazin-3(4H)-one 2-D-glucoside + UDP.

nodes.label: GO:0035500
nodes.Name: MH2 domain binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to a MH2 (MAD homology 2) protein domain. The MH2 domain is found at the carboxy-terminus of MAD related proteins such as Smads. The MH2 domain mediates interaction with a wide variety of proteins and provides specificity and selectivity to Smad function and also is critical for mediating interactions in Smad oligomers.

nodes.label: GO:0072331
nodes.Name: signal transduction by p53 class mediator

nodes.label: GO:1901798

nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of signal transduction by p53 class mediator.

nodes.label: GO:0050124

nodes.Definition: The process in which sporangiospores, a type of asexual spore found in fungi, are formed. Sporangiospores are formed within sac-like structure, the sporangium, following the division of the cytoplasm.

nodes.label: GO:0009314
nodes.Name: response to radiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an electromagnetic radiation stimulus. Electromagnetic radiation is a propagating wave in space with electric and magnetic components. These components oscillate at right angles to each other and to the direction of propagation.

nodes.label: GO:0042011

nodes.Definition: Binding to interleukin-16.

nodes.label: GO:0042018

nodes.label: GO:0097299

nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the hydrolysis of internal, alpha-peptide bonds in a polypeptide chain by a mechanism in which the sulfhydryl group of a cysteine residue at the active center acts as a nucleophile, and contributing to plant-type hypersensitive response, the rapid, localized death of plant cells in response to invasion by a pathogen.

nodes.label: GO:0050960

nodes.Definition: The series of events in which a temperature stimulus is received and converted into a molecular signal as part of thermoception.

nodes.label: GO:0050961

nodes.Definition: The series of events in which a temperature stimulus is received and converted into a molecular signal as part of sensory perception.

nodes.label: GO:0052877

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which a CH-NH2 group acts as a hydrogen or electron donor and a copper protein is the acceptor.

nodes.label: GO:0032831
nodes.Name: positive regulation of CD4-positive, CD25-positive, alpha-beta regulatory T cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of differentiation of CD4-positive, CD25-positive, alpha-beta regulatory T cells.

nodes.label: GO:1901946

nodes.label: GO:1900117

nodes.label: GO:0050954

nodes.label: GO:0050979
nodes.Name: magnetoreception by sensory perception of mechanical stimulus
nodes.Definition: The series of events required for an organism to receive a mechanical stimulus relating to a magnetic field, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. A magnetic field exerts a torque on a ferromagnetic material (e.g. magnetite) or on a material with diamagnetic anisotropy; organisms that can detect this torque can use it to determine the orientation of the magnetic field.

nodes.label: GO:0048639
nodes.Name: positive regulation of developmental growth

nodes.label: GO:1905043

nodes.label: GO:0044129

nodes.Definition: Any process in which the symbiont activates or maintains its progression from an initial condition to a later condition, within the cells or tissues of the host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in the symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0016120

nodes.label: GO:2001015

nodes.label: GO:0010543

nodes.Definition: A series of progressive, overlapping events triggered by exposure of the platelets to subendothelial tissue. These events include shape change, adhesiveness, aggregation, and release reactions. When carried through to completion, these events lead to the formation of a stable hemostatic plug.

nodes.label: GO:0044370

nodes.label: GO:0016517

nodes.Definition: The series of molecular signals initiated by interleukin-12 binding to its receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.label: GO:0004275

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol) + L-alanyl-tRNA(Ala) = 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-1'-(3'-O-L-alanyl)-sn-glycerol + tRNA(Ala).

nodes.label: GO:0032939
nodes.Name: positive regulation of translation in response to oxidative stress
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of translation as a result of oxidative stress, a state often resulting from exposure to high levels of reactive oxygen species, e.g. superoxide anions, hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), and hydroxyl radicals.

nodes.label: GO:0075252

nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of uredospore formation, a process in which an asexual, dikaryotic, often rusty-colored spore, is formed in a structure called a uredinium.

nodes.label: GO:0075253
nodes.Name: positive regulation of uredospore formation
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of uredospore formation, a process in which an asexual, dikaryotic, often rusty-colored spore, is formed in a structure called a uredinium.

nodes.label: GO:0000700
nodes.Name: mismatch base pair DNA N-glycosylase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the removal of single bases present in mismatches by the cleavage the N-C1' glycosidic bond between the target damaged DNA base and the deoxyribose sugar. The reaction releases a free base and leaves an apurinic/apyrimidinic (AP) site.

nodes.label: GO:0075307

Conidia are haploid cells genetically identical to their haploid parent. They are produced by conversion of hyphal elements, or are borne on sporogenous cells on or within specialized structures termed conidiophores, and participate in dispersal of the fungus.

nodes.label: GO:1903666

nodes.label: GO:0045062

nodes.label: GO:0051135

nodes.label: GO:0014741

nodes.label: GO:0070489

nodes.label: GO:0071593

nodes.Definition: The adhesion of one lymphocyte to one or more other lymphocytes via adhesion molecules.

nodes.label: GO:0060554
nodes.Name: necroptotic process
nodes.Definition: A programmed necrotic cell death process which begins when a cell receives a signal (e.g. a ligand binding to a death receptor or to a Toll-like receptor), and proceeds through a series of biochemical events (signaling pathways), characterized by activation of receptor-interacting serine/threonine-protein kinase 1 and/or 3 (RIPK1/3, also called RIP1/3) and by critical dependence on mixed lineage kinase domain-like (MLKL), and which typically lead to common morphological features of necrotic cell death. nodes.label: GO:0016746

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the transfer of an acyl group from one compound (donor) to another (acceptor).

nodes.label: GO:0019162

nodes.label: GO:0002680

nodes.Definition: The process in which a lymphoid progenitor cell becomes committed to becoming a pro-T cell.

nodes.label: GO:2000400

nodes.label: GO:0072193

nodes.label: GO:2000061

nodes.label: GO:1902227

nodes.label: GO:0004237

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of a dipeptide.

nodes.Definition: Any apoptotic process in a keratinocyte. A keratinocyte is an epidermal cell which synthesizes keratin and undergoes a characteristic change as it moves upward from the basal layers of the epidermis to the cornified (horny) layer of the skin.

nodes.label: GO:0060103

nodes.label: GO:0060104
nodes.Name: surface coat of collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix
nodes.Definition: An electron dense, amorphous envelope that comprises the outermost layer of the cuticle. The surface coat is loosely apposed to the epicuticle, has distinct biochemical properties, is synthesized by cells other than the underlying hypodermis, and is labile. In addition to serving as a lubricant to protect against abrasion and dehydration, the surface coat may also play important roles in infection and immune evasion. An example of this component is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.

G-CSF binds to the receptor (CSF3R).

nodes.label: GO:0003905

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: DNA with alkylated base + H2O = DNA with abasic site + alkylated base. This reaction is the hydrolysis of DNA by cleavage of the N-C1' glycosidic bond between the target damaged DNA base and the deoxyribose sugar to remove an alkylated base, leaving an apyrimidinic or apurinic site.

nodes.label: GO:0052820

nodes.label: GO:0014895
nodes.Name: smooth muscle hypertrophy
nodes.Definition: The enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of an organ due to an increase in size of its smooth muscle cells without cell division. Physiological hypertrophy is a normal process during development, and can also occur in mature structures on demand. In the uterus, smooth muscle cells undergo hypertrophy during pregnancy.

nodes.label: GO:0014896
nodes.Name: muscle hypertrophy
nodes.Definition: The muscle system process that results in enlargement or overgrowth of all or part of a muscle organ due to an increase in the size of its muscle cells. Physiological hypertrophy is a normal process during development (it stops in cardiac muscle after adolescence) and can also be brought on in response to demand. In athletes cardiac and skeletal muscles undergo hypertrophy stimulated by increasing muscle activity on exercise. Smooth muscle cells in the uterus undergo hypertrophy during pregnancy.

nodes.label: GO:1905180

nodes.Definition: The series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a Wnt protein to a frizzled family receptor on the surface of the target cell, followed by propagation of the signal via beta-catenin, and ending with a change in transcription of target genes involved in the negative regulation of apoptotic process.

nodes.label: GO:0052622

nodes.label: GO:0042285

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a xylosyl group to an acceptor molecule, typically another carbohydrate or a lipid.

nodes.label: GO:0047284

nodes.label: GO:0097507

nodes.label: GO:0014888
nodes.Name: striated muscle adaptation
nodes.Definition: Any process in which striated muscle adapts, with consequent modifications to structural and/or functional phenotypes, in response to a stimulus. Stimuli include contractile activity, loading conditions, substrate supply, and environmental factors. These adaptive events occur in both muscle fibers and associated structures (motoneurons and capillaries), and they involve alterations in regulatory mechanisms, contractile properties and metabolic capacities.

nodes.label: GO:0075287
nodes.Name: positive regulation of sporangiospore formation
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates, maintains or increases the frequency, rate or extent of sporangiospore formation, a process in which sporangiospores, a type of asexual spore found in fungi, are formed. Sporangiospores are formed within sac-like structure, the sporangium, following the division of the cytoplasm.

nodes.label: GO:0004203

nodes.label: GO:0008219
nodes.Name: cell death
nodes.Definition: Any biological process that results in permanent cessation of all vital functions of a cell. A cell should be considered dead when any one of the following molecular or morphological criteria is met: (1) the cell has lost the integrity of its plasma membrane; (2) the cell, including its nucleus, has undergone complete fragmentation into discrete bodies (frequently referred to as apoptotic bodies). The cell corpse (or its fragments) may be engulfed by an adjacent cell in vivo, but engulfment of whole cells should not be considered a strict criteria to define cell death as, under some circumstances, live engulfed cells can be released from phagosomes (see PMID:18045538).

nodes.label: GO:0016265
nodes.Name: obsolete death
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. A permanent cessation of all vital functions: the end of life; can be applied to a whole organism or to a part of an organism.

nodes.label: GO:0008597

nodes.label: GO:0035941

nodes.label: GO:0010657
nodes.Name: muscle cell apoptotic process
nodes.Definition: A form of programmed cell death induced by external or internal signals that trigger the activity of proteolytic caspases, whose actions dismantle a muscle cell and result in its death. A muscle cell is a mature contractile cell, commonly known as a myocyte, that forms one of three kinds of muscle.

nodes.label: GO:0070976
nodes.Name: TIR domain binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to a Toll-Interleukin receptor (TIR) domain of a protein. The TIR domain is an intracellular 200 residue domain that is found in the Toll protein, the interleukin-1 receptor (IL-1R), and MyD88; it contains three highly-conserved regions, and mediates protein-protein interactions between the Toll-like receptors (TLRs) and signal-transduction components.

nodes.label: GO:0031507
nodes.Name: heterochromatin formation
nodes.Definition: An epigenetic gene silencing mechanism in which chromatin is compacted into heterochromatin, resulting in a chromatin conformation refractory to transcription. This process starts with heterochromatin nucleation, its spreading, and ends with heterochromatin boundary formation.

nodes.label: GO:1904497
nodes.Name: heterochromatin formation
nodes.Definition: An epigenetic gene silencing mechanism in which chromatin is compacted into heterochromatin, resulting in a chromatin conformation refractory to transcription. This process starts with heterochromatin nucleation, its spreading, and ends with heterochromatin boundary formation.

nodes.label: GO:0060105

nodes.label: GO:1902041

nodes.Definition: The process in which a relatively unspecialized precursor cell acquires specialized features of a lymphocyte. nodes.Definition: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a cardiac myoblast. A cardiac myoblast is a precursor cell that has been committed to a cardiac muscle cell fate but retains the ability to divide and proliferate throughout life.

nodes.label: GO:0070268

nodes.Definition: A type of programmed cell death that occurs in the epidermis, morphologically and biochemically distinct from apoptosis. It leads to the formation of corneocytes, i.e. dead keratinocytes containing an amalgam of specific proteins (e.g., keratin, loricrin, SPR and involucrin) and lipids (e.g., fatty acids and ceramides), which are necessary for the function of the cornified skin layer (mechanical resistance, elasticity, water repellence and structural stability).

nodes.label: GO:0009061

The main components of the endomembrane system are endoplasmic reticulum, Golgi bodies, vesicles, cell membrane and nuclear envelope. Members of the endomembrane system pass materials through each other or though the use of vesicles. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0048521

nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of behavior, the internally coordinated responses (actions or inactions) of whole living organisms (individuals or groups) to internal or external stimuli.

nodes.label: GO:0032273

nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the process of creating protein polymers.

nodes.label: GO:0072556

nodes.Definition: A specialized area of membrane of the host axon terminal that faces the plasma membrane of the host neuron or muscle fiber with which the axon terminal establishes a synaptic junction; many host synaptic junctions exhibit structural presynaptic characteristics, such as conical, electron-dense internal protrusions, that distinguish it from the remainder of the axon plasma membrane.

nodes.label: GO:0045068

nodes.Definition: The multiplication or reproduction of osteoclasts, resulting in the expansion of an osteoclast cell population. nodes.label: GO:0044127

nodes.Definition: Any process in which the symbiont regulates its progression from an initial condition to a later condition, within the cells or tissues of the host organism. This may (but not necessarily) include a filamentous growth form, and also can include secretion of proteases and lipases to break down. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in the symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0044131

nodes.Definition: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the atrioventricular (AV) node over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The AV node is part of the cardiac conduction system that controls the timing of ventricle contraction by receiving electrical signals from the sinoatrial (SA) node and relaying them to the His-Purkinje system.

nodes.label: GO:0060922
nodes.Name: atrioventricular node cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of an atrioventricular (AV) node cell. AV node cells are pacemaker cells that are found in the atrioventricular node.

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: 2 dimethylallyl diphosphate = diphosphate + lavandulyl diphosphate.

nodes.label: GO:2000491
nodes.Name: positive regulation of hepatic stellate cell activation
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of hepatic stellate cell activation.

nodes.label: GO:0070059
nodes.Name: intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway in response to endoplasmic reticulum stress
nodes.Definition: The series of molecular signals in which an intracellular signal is conveyed to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway is induced in response to a stimulus indicating endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered. ER stress usually results from the accumulation of unfolded or misfolded proteins in the ER lumen.

nodes.label: GO:1902237
nodes.Name: positive regulation of endoplasmic reticulum stress-induced intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway
nodes.Definition: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of an endoplasmic reticulum stress-induced intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:0034360
nodes.Name: chylomicron remnant
nodes.Definition: A lipoprotein particle that is derived from a mature chylomicron particle by the removal of triglycerides from the chylomicron core by lipoprotein lipase and the subsequent loss of surface components. It characteristically contains apolipoprotein E (APOE) and is cleared from the blood by the liver.

nodes.label: GO:0042627
nodes.Name: chylomicron
nodes.Definition: A large lipoprotein particle (diameter 75-1200 nm) composed of a central core of triglycerides and cholesterol surrounded by a protein-phospholipid coating. The proteins include one molecule of apolipoprotein B-48 and may include a variety of apolipoproteins, including APOAs, APOCs and APOE. Chylomicrons are found in blood or lymph and carry lipids from the intestines into other body tissues.

nodes.label: GO:0097345
nodes.Name: mitochondrial outer membrane permeabilization
nodes.Definition: The process by which the mitochondrial outer membrane becomes permeable to the passing of proteins and other molecules from the intermembrane space to the cytosol as part of the apoptotic signaling pathway.

nodes.label: GO:0002299
nodes.Name: alpha-beta intraepithelial T cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: The process in which a precursor cell type acquires the specialized features of an alpha-beta intraepithelial T cell. Intraepithelial T cells are found among epithelial cells in mucosal areas and have distinct phenotypes and developmental pathways.

nodes.label: GO:0007114
nodes.Name: cell budding
nodes.Definition: A form of asexual reproduction, occurring in certain bacteria and fungi (e.g. yeasts) and some primitive animals in which an individual arises from a daughter cell formed by pinching off a part of the parent cell. The budlike outgrowths so formed may sometimes remain attached to the parent cell.

nodes.label: GO:0032463
nodes.Name: negative regulation of protein homooligomerization
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of protein homooligomerization.

nodes.label: GO:0050957
nodes.Name: equilibrioception
nodes.Definition: The series of events required for an organism to receive an orientational stimulus, convert it to a molecular signal, and recognize and characterize the signal. Equilibrioception refers to a combination of processes by which an organism can perceive its orientation with respect to gravity. In animals, stimuli come from labyrinth system of the inner ears, monitoring the direction of motion; visual stimuli, with information on orientation and motion; pressure receptors, which tell the organism which body surfaces are in contact with the ground; and proprioceptive cues, which report which parts of the body are in motion.

nodes.label: GO:0050973
nodes.Name: detection of mechanical stimulus involved in equilibrioception
nodes.Definition: The series of events involved in equilibrioception in which a mechanical stimulus is received and converted into a molecular signal. During equilibrioception, mechanical stimuli may be in the form of input from pressure receptors or from the labyrinth system of the inner ears.

nodes.label: GO:0070551
nodes.Name: endoribonuclease activity, cleaving siRNA-paired mRNA
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the endonucleolytic cleavage of the mRNA in a double-stranded RNA molecule formed by the base pairing of an mRNA with an siRNA, yielding 5'-phosphomonoesters.

nodes.label: GO:0035181
nodes.Name: larval burrowing behavior
nodes.Definition: Digging into the substrate by non-feeding larvae in search for food-free sites suitable for pupation.

nodes.label: GO:0070853
nodes.Name: myosin VI binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to a class VI myosin. The myosin VI heavy chain has a single IQ motif in the neck and a tail region with a coiled coil domain followed by a unique globular domain, a unique insertion that enables myosin VI to move towards the pointed or minus end of actin filaments.

nodes.label: GO:0034529
nodes.Name: obsolete 2-hydroxy-3-carboxy-benzalpyruvate hydratase-aldolase activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Catalysis of the reaction: 2-hydroxy-3-carboxybenzalpyruvate + H2O = 3-formylsalicylic acid + pyruvate.

nodes.label: GO:0070924
nodes.Name: regulatory ncRNA-mediated heterochromatin formation
nodes.Definition: A heterochromatin formation-based gene silencing process mediated by a regulatory non-coding RNA molecule that occur before the beginning of trancription.

nodes.label: GO:0008845
nodes.Name: obsolete endonuclease VIII activity
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. (Was not defined before being made obsolete).

nodes.label: GO:0019961
nodes.Name: interferon binding
nodes.Definition: Binding to an interferon, a protein produced by the immune systems of many animals in response to a challenge by a foreign agent.

nodes.label: GO:0033721

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: an aldehyde + NADP+ + H2O = an acid + NADPH + H+.

nodes.label: GO:0047552

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: a 2-oxoaldehyde + NADP+ + H2O = a 2-oxo acid + NADPH + H+.

nodes.label: GO:0075276
nodes.Name: regulation of telium development
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of telium development, a process that leads to the formation of a teliospore-bearing sorus of the rust fungi.

nodes.label: GO:0018923

nodes.label: GO:1904829
nodes.Name: regulation of aortic smooth muscle cell differentiation
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of aortic smooth muscle cell differentiation.

nodes.label: GO:1901938
nodes.Name: (-)-exo-alpha-bergamotene metabolic process
nodes.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving (-)-exo-alpha-bergamotene.

nodes.label: GO:0043369
nodes.Name: CD4-positive or CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell lineage commitment
nodes.Definition: The process in which an immature T cell commits to CD4-positive T cell lineage or the CD8-positive lineage of alpha-beta T cells.

nodes.label: GO:0047231
nodes.Name: pyridoxine 5'-O-beta-D-glucosyltransferase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: pyridoxine + UDP-D-glucose = 5'-O-beta-D-glucosylpyridoxine + H+ + UDP.

nodes.label: GO:0008630
nodes.Name: intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway in response to DNA damage
nodes.Definition: The series of molecular signals in which an intracellular signal is conveyed to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway is induced by the detection of DNA damage, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

nodes.label: GO:1902229
nodes.Name: regulation of intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway in response to DNA damage
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway in response to DNA damage.

nodes.label: GO:2000850
nodes.Name: negative regulation of glucocorticoid secretion
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of glucocorticoid secretion.

nodes.label: GO:0043501
nodes.Name: skeletal muscle adaptation
nodes.Definition: Any process in which skeletal muscles change their phenotypic profiles in response to altered functional demands and a variety of signals.

nodes.label: GO:0043503
nodes.Name: skeletal muscle fiber adaptation
nodes.Definition: Any process in which the skeletal muscle fibers change their phenotypic profiles in response to altered functional demands and a variety of signals. Muscle fibers are formed by the maturation of myotubes. They can be classed as slow, intermediate/fast or fast.

nodes.label: GO:0032922
nodes.Name: circadian regulation of gene expression
nodes.Definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression such that an expression pattern recurs with a regularity of approximately 24 hours.

nodes.label: GO:0036092
nodes.Name: phosphatidylinositol-3-phosphate biosynthetic process
nodes.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of phosphatidylinositol-3-phosphate, a phosphatidylinositol monophosphate carrying the phosphate group at the 3-position.

nodes.label: GO:0014906
nodes.Name: myotube cell development involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
nodes.Definition: The process aimed at the progression of a myotube cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell. This occurs as part of the process of skeletal muscle regeneration. Myotubes are multinucleated cells that are formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.

nodes.label: GO:0050738
nodes.Name: fructosyltransferase activity
nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a fructosyl group to an acceptor molecule, typically another carbohydrate or a lipid.

nodes.label: GO:0033649

nodes.Definition: A membrane-bounded organelle as it is found in the host cell in which chromosomes are housed and replicated. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0042025
nodes.Name: host cell nucleus
nodes.Definition: A membrane-bounded organelle as it is found in the host cell in which chromosomes are housed and replicated. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0071531
nodes.Name: obsolete Rel homology domain-mediated complex assembly
nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. A process of protein complex assembly in which the arrangement and bonding together of the set of components that form the protein complex is mediated by a Rel homology domain (RHD) interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0008940

nodes.label: GO:0050503

nodes.Definition: Catalysis of the reaction: trehalose 6-phosphate + phosphate = glucose 6-phosphate + beta-D-glucose 1-phosphate.

nodes.label: GO:0014905
nodes.Name: myoblast fusion involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
nodes.Definition: A process in which non-proliferating myoblasts, after migrating to the site of injury, fuse into existing damaged fibers or fuse to myotubes to form new fibers, as part of the process of skeletal muscle regeneration. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

nodes.label: GO:0014908
nodes.Name: myotube differentiation involved in skeletal muscle regeneration
nodes.Definition: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a myotube cell. Myotube differentiation starts with myoblast fusion and the appearance of specific cell markers (this is the cell development step). Then individual myotubes can fuse to form bigger myotubes and start to contract. This process occurs as part of the process of skeletal muscle regeneration. Myotubes are multinucleated cells that are formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.

nodes.label: GO:0010572
nodes.Name: positive regulation of platelet activation
nodes.Definition: Any process that increases the rate or frequency of platelet activation. Platelet activation is a series of progressive, overlapping events triggered by exposure of the platelets to subendothelial tissue.

nodes.label: GO:0014735

nodes.label: GO:0039714

nodes.Definition: A cytoplasmic viral factory that consists of a double-membrane bound vesicle. Has a diameter of 200-300nm and is derived from the endoplasmic reticulum or Golgi apparatus. Produced by Picornaviridae, Nidovirales, Arteriviridae and Coronaviridae.

nodes.label: GO:0018474

nodes.label: GO:0043415

nodes.label: GO:0034298

nodes.Definition: The formation of conidia by the conversion of a pre-existing hypha. An arthrospore is produced by the last cell on a hypha breaking off and dispersing. Usually the walls thicken and the cell(s) separates before swelling of each spore. Sometimes further septa form in each cell prior to disarticulation.

nodes.label: GO:0004559

nodes.label: GO:0036216

nodes.Definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stem cell factor (SCF) stimulus.

nodes.label: GO:0085019
nodes.Name: formation of tubovesicular network for nutrient acquisition
nodes.Definition: The assembly of a symbiont-induced complex organelle that comprises of multiple protein and lipid domains for the purpose of obtaining nutrients from its host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.label: GO:0014736
nodes.Name: negative regulation of muscle atrophy
nodes.Definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of muscle atrophy.

nodes.label: GO:0014889
nodes.Name: muscle atrophy
nodes.Definition: A process, occurring in the muscle, that is characterized by a decrease in protein content, fiber diameter, force production and fatigue resistance in response to different conditions such as starvation, aging and disuse.

nodes.label: GO:0000263

nodes.Definition: OBSOLETE. Subunit of a heterotrimeric G-protein GTPase that contains the guanine nucleotide binding site and possesses GTPase activity.

nodes.label: GO:0070869

nodes.Definition: An epigenetic gene silencing mechanism in which chromatin is compacted into heterochromatin, resulting in a chromatin conformation refractory to transcription. This process starts with heterochromatin nucleation, its spreading, and ends with heterochromatin boundary formation.

nodes.label: GO:0008378

nodes.label: GO:0038151

nodes.Definition: The series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of the C-C chemokine CCL2 to a C-C chemokine type 2 receptor (CCR2) on the surface of a target cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.label: GO:0045782

nodes.label: GO:0044418
